Leaders around the world have widely condemned President Trump’s racist and disgraceful remarks about Haiti. But actions speak far louder than words. It is incumbent upon world leaders and President Trump to contribute to the cholera trust fund.
It is unconscionable that the richest nations in the world are abdicating their duty to support #Haiti's cholera trust fund.

The 2010 earthquake was devastating enough and Haiti is still suffering from its-after effects. Cholera has exacerbated the crisis. Many Haitians who thankfully survived the disease lost their homes and livelihoods during their recovery because they were unable to work.

Shamefully, it took six years for the UN to acknowledge and apologize for UN peacekeepers’ role in #Haiti's cholera crisis but launched a $400 million Haiti Cholera Response Multi-Partner Trust Fund to address it and aid victims.

Eight years ago, Haiti was struck by a double whammy in the form of a major earthquake and a cholera epidemic. The former was unpreventable, but the spread of cholera was indisputably the result of human error.

Today is the anniversary of the earthquake that 8 years ago shook Haiti to its core. Few if any nations have withstood so many natural disasters & its citizens’ resilience has been remarkable. Let us reaffirm our commitment to the country to aid its ongoing efforts to rebuild.
